1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,872
I thought I would.

2
00:00:01,032 --> 00:00:03,174
Can you hear me?

3
00:00:03,194 --> 00:00:07,341
I thought I would preface this talk by telling you, you're all going to be very disappointed.

4
00:00:09,804 --> 00:00:19,117
When Simon emailed me and said, we'd like you to do a presentation on your community, I said, I don't have a community.

5
00:00:19,137 --> 00:00:23,202
And then very foolishly I said, I can tell you how to establish a non-community.

6
00:00:24,077 --> 00:00:28,742
So this was way back, and I tested him a little bit before this conference.

7
00:00:28,763 --> 00:00:32,767
He said, you really want me to talk about how I ended up in a place without a community?

8
00:00:33,426 --> 00:00:35,168
I said, sure.

9
00:00:35,189 --> 00:00:38,713
So here I am, explaining to you how I got to a place without a community.

10
00:00:41,595 --> 00:00:43,377
Now the question is, do you want me to carry on?

11
00:00:46,621 --> 00:00:49,984
Thank you.

12
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:54,228
Well, what it is, it's a story.

13
00:00:54,569 --> 00:00:58,380
So if you just sit back and enjoy a story, then it works.

14
00:00:58,399 --> 00:01:02,472
You don't expect to learn anything.

15
00:01:04,477 --> 00:01:05,661
Well, that's your story.

16
00:01:05,680 --> 00:01:06,403
That's my story.

17
00:01:07,430 --> 00:01:26,299
So in 98, I returned from Sri Lanka not feeling very well, and I decided to spend the rest of the rainy season, which is our summertime, in a place which was full of good air and a lively and supportive atmosphere, which was London.

18
00:01:26,903 --> 00:01:36,420
I got a contract going with the chief monk at the Sri Lankan Buddhist Vihara in London.

19
00:01:37,421 --> 00:01:41,388
And he very kindly gave me a room at the back end of the monastery where I could just carry on.

20
00:01:41,909 --> 00:01:48,219
And by the end of that, I hoped that there'd be some clarification as to whether I wanted to go back to the East or stay in the West.

21
00:01:49,111 --> 00:02:02,326
Unfortunately during that time the monk who was teaching the meditation, a young Asian monk, decided on receiving British nationality to leave and get married.

22
00:02:02,593 --> 00:02:08,861
So, not an uncommon, okay.

23
00:02:08,882 --> 00:02:13,888
So, they asked me, I said, well, you know, I really don't want to, etc., etc., but you have to.

24
00:02:14,969 --> 00:02:29,108
So, I began teaching, and, you know, to my surprise, there was some growth in the audience and all that, and

25
00:02:30,099 --> 00:02:39,412
By the end of a year or so, I'd come to realize that, A, I didn't want to go back to the East.

26
00:02:39,752 --> 00:02:40,955
My time there was over.

27
00:02:41,634 --> 00:02:50,668
And B, if I wanted to stay in the West, there was no way I would get the support I needed to live the life I wanted to, which was a solitudinous life at the end of a valley.

28
00:02:52,389 --> 00:02:55,032
And I would have to earn my living.

29
00:02:55,473 --> 00:02:57,036
And to do that, you have to teach.

30
00:02:57,842 --> 00:03:18,044
So I reluctantly decided to teach and I went off on a long retreat at one of my teacher's place, Saida Upandita, that's the Burmese connection, the meditation I teach is Burmese, the Mahasi Saida tradition.

31
00:03:19,492 --> 00:03:22,617
And I spent the season there.

32
00:03:23,079 --> 00:03:34,336
Now, during that, just before I left, a venerable, I can't remember his name now, the chief monk who died at London.

33
00:03:35,478 --> 00:03:40,026
Can you remember his name?

34
00:03:40,045 --> 00:03:40,385
No, no, no.

35
00:03:40,506 --> 00:03:40,967
In London.

36
00:03:42,088 --> 00:03:42,530
In London.

37
00:03:42,550 --> 00:03:42,750
In London.

38
00:03:44,502 --> 00:03:45,582
Yeah, I can't remember.

39
00:03:45,682 --> 00:03:46,743
Anyway, he died.

40
00:03:47,444 --> 00:03:48,366
Let's just say he died.

41
00:03:49,306 --> 00:03:57,194
So he... Seemingly, along with his name.

42
00:04:03,281 --> 00:04:08,105
So I...

43
00:04:08,205 --> 00:04:10,108
So he had got very upset with me.

44
00:04:10,228 --> 00:04:11,330
I'll tell you why later.

45
00:04:11,349 --> 00:04:12,770
So I wrote this...

46
00:04:14,810 --> 00:04:17,314
So I wrote this letter explaining my position.

47
00:04:18,274 --> 00:04:25,646
And when I got to the monastery, I began meditating, again in the very lugubrious and wonderful air of Rangoon.

48
00:04:26,406 --> 00:04:32,615
And I asked people not to give me any letters or anything like that until the end of the retreat.

49
00:04:33,507 --> 00:04:44,298
A letter was handed to me, and the abbot said, in so many words, I'm tremendously disgusted with you.

50
00:04:44,860 --> 00:04:46,581
When you come back, you can stay for two nights.

51
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:48,023
That was it.

52
00:04:48,603 --> 00:04:51,286
I'm looking at this letter thinking, I've been thrown out of house and home.

53
00:04:52,307 --> 00:04:56,271
So I get back, and of course I have a chat with him, and everything is reconciled.

54
00:04:56,612 --> 00:05:01,658
But I realised that I didn't have a power over my own life, that he could just kick me out when he felt like it.

55
00:05:02,329 --> 00:05:05,192
Now the reason he took that position was very simple.

56
00:05:06,213 --> 00:05:13,440
Can you imagine setting up a business and somebody comes along who comes along as a helper or at least begins to help you.

57
00:05:14,502 --> 00:05:18,887
On the quiet, without you really knowing, he's setting up his own business with your clients.

58
00:05:20,307 --> 00:05:21,028
This is what I was doing.

59
00:05:22,069 --> 00:05:27,855
I was setting up my own little sangha from the sangha that he had himself established at the Vihara.

60
00:05:27,875 --> 00:05:29,016
So he's very upset.

61
00:05:29,036 --> 00:05:29,737
I can't understand it.

62
00:05:30,072 --> 00:05:35,447
So, I decided then to leave the Hary, you see.

63
00:05:35,468 --> 00:05:43,170
At that point, I had the help of a young Dutchman who was doing a PhD in London, Mattes, we know him, Mattes.

64
00:05:43,336 --> 00:05:49,723
And that was a time when websites were just about coming in, 2000, 2001.

65
00:05:50,845 --> 00:05:55,230
So we set up a website and we put to people this vision.

66
00:05:55,490 --> 00:06:08,567
And the vision was of a Mahasi meditation center right there in the middle of London, servicing London, which would not only offer evening classes, but the ability to do long retreats, just like in Rangoon.

67
00:06:09,526 --> 00:06:12,670
And my little mantra was, where there's suffering, there's the end of it.

68
00:06:13,389 --> 00:06:14,651
And it was here, it was in London.

69
00:06:14,971 --> 00:06:16,254
So why go anywhere else?

70
00:06:17,355 --> 00:06:26,125
So we collected this money and there now was a series of blunders which led to this catastrophe.

71
00:06:26,144 --> 00:06:30,550
The first one was that where were we going to have this centre?

72
00:06:30,569 --> 00:06:38,418
So we decided that it was going to be in the north because in the north there were two Sri Lankan women who were great supporters who wanted us to go there.

73
00:06:38,973 --> 00:06:47,165
I didn't want to stay in the west of London because that would undermine, again, this relationship I had with the abbot.

74
00:06:48,067 --> 00:06:49,528
Sorry?

75
00:06:50,470 --> 00:06:52,934
No, no, no, he's dead long years ago.

76
00:06:53,754 --> 00:06:56,238
So, it'll come to me.

77
00:06:56,540 --> 00:07:05,949
So we moved to the north and we moved into an area that was full of Greek Cypriots and Jews.

78
00:07:07,791 --> 00:07:13,137
So there was not a single ability to have any local people who would come to the meeting.

79
00:07:13,939 --> 00:07:16,100
That was the first blunder.

80
00:07:17,141 --> 00:07:22,327
The second blunder was the opening ceremony.

81
00:07:22,848 --> 00:07:25,209
I realised that I didn't want to disturb the neighbours.

82
00:07:25,730 --> 00:07:34,100
I knew that round about 30 odd people would come from the west of London, but there was also a rather large local Sri Lankan community.

83
00:07:34,639 --> 00:07:36,641
So I decided to have two ceremonies.

84
00:07:36,901 --> 00:07:48,213
The first was the opening ceremony, which would just bless the property, and the second one would be the blessing ceremony of this particular lovely statue that the abbot gave me for this centre.

85
00:07:49,072 --> 00:07:59,026
So the opening ceremony, all the English people came and with lots of food and it was all very grand, it was all very lovely.

86
00:07:59,846 --> 00:08:05,154
And when it came to the Sri Lankan opening centre, three people turned up.

87
00:08:05,175 --> 00:08:09,060
They were absolutely insulted that they'd not been invited to the opening.

88
00:08:09,661 --> 00:08:11,704
So I lost their support.

89
00:08:13,067 --> 00:08:18,196
Then I opened up and said, you know, we're going to have classes here and weekend retreats.

90
00:08:18,536 --> 00:08:22,302
Well, it takes two hours to go from the west of London to the north.

91
00:08:23,285 --> 00:08:24,065
So nobody came.

92
00:08:25,487 --> 00:08:29,574
So there I am in splendid isolation in the north of London.

93
00:08:29,992 --> 00:08:34,937
with 25,000 pounds, 30,000 euros to spend.

94
00:08:36,359 --> 00:08:40,744
And the rent is 1,200 euros a month.

95
00:08:41,484 --> 00:08:45,749
And I'm stuck there on my own, thinking, well, this is a catastrophe.

96
00:08:46,830 --> 00:08:47,210
Slowly.

97
00:08:47,831 --> 00:08:51,514
Then comes the third catastrophe, the third blunder.

98
00:08:53,096 --> 00:08:59,341
I began to advertise it in all the places around North London.

99
00:08:59,845 --> 00:09:07,120
and I had two young men who were ready to cycle everywhere and put these little notices up, meditation, etc., etc.

100
00:09:08,124 --> 00:09:17,684
I'd given all the information to one of the persons who was then quite able on his computer, and he made this lovely sign, which I foolishly failed to check.

101
00:09:22,879 --> 00:09:32,333
After this wonderful spreading of all these notes, they gave me one, and I realised, A, it did not have an address.

102
00:09:36,418 --> 00:09:38,241
And B, the phone number was wrong.

103
00:09:41,145 --> 00:09:45,832
The first meeting on Monday, one person came, the next door neighbour.

104
00:09:48,174 --> 00:09:51,139
On the second meeting Monday, zilch, nobody.

105
00:09:52,139 --> 00:09:57,126
And I said to Matthew, I said, look, I said, September, people organize their lives now.

106
00:09:57,386 --> 00:10:02,793
You know, they go to knitting clubs, violin lessons, whatever it is, they organize it in September for the autumn.

107
00:10:03,894 --> 00:10:07,580
And I said, if nothing happens by the end of this month, nothing's going to happen.

108
00:10:07,600 --> 00:10:10,644
So come the end of the month, nothing's happened, nothing's going to happen.

109
00:10:11,384 --> 00:10:13,827
So I said, look, we're going to have to close this place down.

110
00:10:14,769 --> 00:10:26,825
Now I have to be thankful to the Sri Lankan community, because when I mentioned this to these two women, they really rallied the Sri Lankans to come and try and lift up this dying elephant.

111
00:10:28,606 --> 00:10:37,317
Anyway, we'd already paid this rent, so there's no point in leaving the place.

112
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:48,818
So come the winter, I at least, one of the parts of the vision was realized where we had a retreat in that little house in the north of London for five of us.

113
00:10:49,600 --> 00:10:55,067
And through the Bodhisattva supermarket, Asda, we were able to get our food every week.

114
00:10:55,788 --> 00:10:58,110
And we did what I thought was an excellent retreat.

115
00:10:58,171 --> 00:10:59,692
Very quiet, very still.

116
00:10:59,753 --> 00:11:00,754
It was really quite wonderful.

117
00:11:02,035 --> 00:11:04,899
But then, of course, there came the realization that I just couldn't go on.

118
00:11:05,639 --> 00:11:07,001
And that the whole thing had been

119
00:11:07,167 --> 00:11:08,889
and a mitigated disaster.

120
00:11:10,110 --> 00:11:28,729
So in that there, through the support of a close friend who'd been on retreat with me, he got in contact with somebody he knew, the bachelors, whom some of you know, from Gaia House.

121
00:11:29,190 --> 00:11:34,575
And it was just at that point that Gaia House were short of a teacher, wanted a resident teacher.

122
00:11:35,381 --> 00:11:46,073
So I immediately accepted the offer and found myself invited to Gaia House and having arrived there realised they didn't want me.

123
00:11:47,775 --> 00:11:53,162
I stayed there in this sort of limbo place for four years.

124
00:11:54,102 --> 00:11:59,369
And it was after one year that I realised that there wasn't any future for me at Gaia House.

125
00:11:59,688 --> 00:12:05,034
For those of you who understand the metaphor, it was like being a Catholic priest amongst Quakers.

126
00:12:06,922 --> 00:12:24,238
complete utter nonsense however I do look however I have tremendous gratitude towards Guy Howard it's a really fabulous centre and they allowed me to run these long meditation retreats eight week retreats which were well attended

127
00:12:25,096 --> 00:12:33,269
And it was there, that having realised I couldn't stay, that I began to think about again having another go at setting up a centre.

128
00:12:34,811 --> 00:12:37,294
Once burnt, well, you've got to burn yourself a bit more.

129
00:12:38,317 --> 00:12:46,068
So we set up a trust and whatnot, and off we went, and I almost made the same blunders again.

130
00:12:46,129 --> 00:12:49,855
Were it not that we just woke up at the right time.

131
00:12:50,341 --> 00:12:55,707
We found a place which was happily, somebody took it from us, they bid it higher.

132
00:12:57,190 --> 00:13:01,754
And then... That would have been a real blunder, frankly.

133
00:13:01,774 --> 00:13:09,725
And eventually we found a place which is on the border of England, in Wales, and easily accessible, fairly easily accessible.

134
00:13:09,745 --> 00:13:14,270
And that's where we established ourselves.

135
00:13:14,291 --> 00:13:15,673
Now...

136
00:13:17,003 --> 00:13:37,677
One decision I've made, two decisions I've made in this whole period of time, was, first of all, to try and maintain the Buddha Dhamma as it was being transmitted to me from the Mahasi tradition especially, but also the Shrainkind, but specifically meditation-wise through the Mahasi tradition.

137
00:13:37,894 --> 00:13:47,830
and not to throw the baby out with the bathwater, not to throw what's good about the tradition, to try and be a traditionalist without being conservative.

138
00:13:49,332 --> 00:13:59,869
And so I tried to maintain very simple forms, which was just taking refuges and precepts, and really centring the whole place upon meditations.

139
00:14:00,894 --> 00:14:04,561
The effectiveness, of course, is that it doesn't attract any Easterners.

140
00:14:05,201 --> 00:14:13,855
And therefore, whatever support there might have come from the East or from Easterners in Britain, it just doesn't come.

141
00:14:16,879 --> 00:14:22,447
The second one was something that I had to come to grips with when I went to Gaia House.

142
00:14:24,250 --> 00:14:29,736
What happened to the teachers was that they were trained like I was.

143
00:14:30,638 --> 00:14:32,039
This is the Vipassana teachers.

144
00:14:32,980 --> 00:14:38,648
You know, people like Christina Fellman and Christy Titmuss and all those.

145
00:14:39,107 --> 00:14:43,234
They were trained like me by Eastern teachers who really demanded blood.

146
00:14:44,235 --> 00:14:49,461
You know, you were up at half past three, sit, walk, sit, walk, sit, walk, sit, walk, drop dead, ten o'clock.

147
00:14:50,081 --> 00:14:51,484
Back up again at half past three.

148
00:14:51,504 --> 00:14:53,346
I mean, it's really full on.

149
00:14:53,629 --> 00:15:08,466
And what had happened over a period of time, the time that I was in Sri Lanka at the monastery, was that of course they had to come to grips with the reality that most people who were coming to meditate just couldn't handle that sort of form.

150
00:15:08,486 --> 00:15:15,975
So very slowly, it's put in a bad way, the meditation taught was becoming watered down.

151
00:15:16,883 --> 00:15:17,783
And I don't think that's fair.

152
00:15:17,884 --> 00:15:18,745
It's not watered down.

153
00:15:18,825 --> 00:15:26,991
It's simply presented in a way that's acceptable for people who really aren't at the level of this very hard practice.

154
00:15:27,011 --> 00:15:34,418
However, when I was there, it was quite obvious that there were a few people who were ready for that sort of practice.

155
00:15:34,438 --> 00:15:44,528
So that was my second decision, was to maintain the heavy, hardcore practice of Vipassana meditation in the Mahadi tradition.

156
00:15:44,508 --> 00:15:48,163
But that necessarily meant a very small centre.

157
00:15:48,866 --> 00:15:53,488
I only take eight meditators and I don't have a long waiting list.

158
00:15:53,788 --> 00:16:17,417
I mean it is very small so I have this I have this place in the middle of Wales with a very small intake and a growing sense that these people who are coming regularly so that's the other thing which is a surprise to me

159
00:16:18,359 --> 00:16:20,743
I have a return rate of something around 70%.

160
00:16:21,003 --> 00:16:30,238
Now, this is where I'm stuck at the moment, and this is where hopefully these talks about establishing community will be of help to me.

161
00:16:30,759 --> 00:16:38,652
I can feel that something needs to be done to make this disparate community contact each other.

162
00:16:38,672 --> 00:16:39,592
They come from everywhere.

163
00:16:39,633 --> 00:16:43,860
They come from all parts of England, sometimes from other parts of Europe.

164
00:16:43,840 --> 00:17:02,000
But when they've got to know each other through the meditation experience, because I always bring the meditation down slowly at the end so there's plenty of time to talk and chat and get to know people, that some of them have made connections, made friendships and even visit each other.

165
00:17:03,212 --> 00:17:10,064
And somehow to let that grow either organically or to do something to aid that process.

166
00:17:11,886 --> 00:17:20,901
But in my experience, what has happened is that I began teaching weekend retreats and then realized that people wanted weeklongs.

167
00:17:21,218 --> 00:17:33,643
And then just before going back now to 99, I was offered a house in Yorkshire near Thirsk, very beautiful, where I ran my first ever 10 week long retreat.

168
00:17:34,265 --> 00:17:36,409
And to my surprise, 30 people came.

169
00:17:36,810 --> 00:17:40,960
Not for the full time, but five or six of them actually stayed the full ten weeks.

170
00:17:41,500 --> 00:17:53,165
So there was this constant feeling by me of feeding back into the people who were working with me the opportunity to work for longer and deeper and deeper and deeper.

171
00:17:53,804 --> 00:18:18,336
And it seems to me now that I'm at this place where unless something happens to connect these people and to create what Vajratara has so eloquently explained in her delivery there, unless I do that, then something's going to give.

172
00:18:18,356 --> 00:18:23,523
It'll either begin to evaporate or it'll either grow.

173
00:18:26,827 --> 00:18:27,689
That's my story.

174
00:18:29,612 --> 00:18:34,941
So any of you who can help me in this little dilemma, I'll be very grateful.

175
00:18:35,481 --> 00:18:40,810
I'm sorry I've been able to say anything about creating community.

176
00:18:44,455 --> 00:18:44,777
Thank you.

177
00:18:48,102 --> 00:18:48,623
What question?

178
00:18:52,429 --> 00:18:54,152
You made a sketch of the face, I did it.

179
00:19:00,847 --> 00:19:01,469
Oh.

180
00:19:03,652 --> 00:19:07,699
Oh, is it?

181
00:19:07,719 --> 00:19:08,200
Oh, I see.

182
00:19:08,220 --> 00:19:09,602
Oh, I'm sorry, Fred.

183
00:19:09,842 --> 00:19:10,542
I should have signalled.

184
00:19:11,925 --> 00:19:14,849
Didn't realise.

185
00:19:15,691 --> 00:19:17,074
No, he was just telling me to speak louder.

186
00:19:20,980 --> 00:19:22,082
Which is a good comment.

187
00:19:23,984 --> 00:19:25,467
That's it.

188
00:19:25,487 --> 00:19:28,070
Oh, there we are.

189
00:19:39,002 --> 00:19:41,086
I don't really appreciate your story.

190
00:19:41,448 --> 00:19:42,269
I love stories.

191
00:19:42,549 --> 00:19:43,030
Thank you.

192
00:19:44,374 --> 00:19:45,736
You can identify with a lot of it.

193
00:19:46,597 --> 00:19:48,843
And my question is the same.

194
00:19:48,962 --> 00:19:53,952
Can anyone give me any advice?

195
00:19:53,972 --> 00:20:00,605
I don't know what it is, but it does seem to be something to do with the right people come together at the right time.

196
00:20:01,008 --> 00:20:04,035
It goes or sometimes it's just not the time.

197
00:20:04,055 --> 00:20:06,721
It evaporates, yes.

198
00:20:07,542 --> 00:20:09,165
It's not actually a component.

199
00:20:09,186 --> 00:20:09,827
No, no, no.

200
00:20:09,847 --> 00:20:10,409
That's the way it is.

201
00:20:11,972 --> 00:20:16,923
At least I can say that Satipaññá has been a flash in the phenomenal universe.

202
00:20:30,201 --> 00:20:40,137
Somebody told me there is a lack of places in Europe where one can do longer vipassana retreats, so I would encourage you to go on.

203
00:20:40,157 --> 00:20:40,498
Thank you.

204
00:20:50,554 --> 00:20:50,994
Yes.

205
00:20:55,378 --> 00:21:04,372
I just wondered, Bansi, whether you'd challenge the idea that you seem to have that it's you that need to do something.

206
00:21:04,392 --> 00:21:10,181
Oh, well, no, that's what I meant, whether to let it grow organically, whether to see what happens, you know, rather than me all the time.

207
00:21:10,401 --> 00:21:12,564
Up until now, it's been me, me, me, you know.

208
00:21:13,025 --> 00:21:20,796
